                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Patauinitatem taceo, quam non tacuit Asinius Pollio. His autem reprehensionibus, quant&ograve; plura, maioraq[ue] Elogia?  
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Gaius Asinius Pollio"/> <!-- LS, I added this one -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                There exists an outspoken and sharp attack on Livy by a learned Frenchman, especially concerning his fellow Gauls. He complains that Livy 
                accused them of vices that were made up. Also Bodin, supporting his ancestors, refutes this, with a slightly milder attitude to Livy. Bodin and
                several others also assuredly criticized several other shortcomings by Livy. That he is excessive in praise of others, yet stingy in criticism;
                that he is immoderate in describing incredible prodigies, unrestrained in inserting direct and indirect speeches, which also Justin observes on
                the basis of Trogus; that he was an unrestrained supporter of his own Romans and not sufficiently honest about others, the Gauls in particular; 
                that in contrast to Polybius he was prejudiced against the troops of Brennus, who were not entirely destroyed, as he, Appianus and Justin made 
                up, but who, having defeated the Tracians, ruled for a long time in the area around Byzantium. Indeed also to Lipsius, if indeed just, the same
                seemed very recently occasionally languid or torpid, and indeed even repetitive. If only Lipsius himself were never more languid or torpid, or 
                repetitive so much. I remain silent about his Patavinity, about which Asinius Pollio did not keep silent. Yet how much more numerous and 
                greater than these criticisms are the tributes!
            </translation>
